# migrated from tests/cases/gen_stop.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test gen_stop]
# gen106 (L1): the learned end-of-sequence token. The autoregressive decode loop
# (gen36-42) generated until a 24-step ceiling cut it off — a hard bound, not a
# learned halt. D-prop1 calls for "an explicit stop token / end relation" so the
# loop ends because the model LEARNED where utterances end. gen106 induces a
# transition to a STOP sentinel at every sentence boundary (a terminal '.' or
# end-of-stream), so STOP competes in the same frequency model as any word.
# It is induced from the taught text, never hand-authored (PRINCIPLES.md).

# A clean sentence is learned to its boundary: decode halts at the learned STOP,
# not at an arbitrary step count.
> learn sequence: birds fly south in winter .
< Learned 4 transition(s).
> say birds
< birds fly south in winter

# The decisive case: STOP is weighed like any continuation. Here "sat" ends the
# utterance twice but continues to "the mat" once — so the model has LEARNED that
# stopping after "sat" is more likely, and halts there even though a real
# continuation exists. A learned end-of-sequence, dominating by frequency.
> learn sequence: the cat sat . the cat sat . the cat sat the mat .
< Learned 8 transition(s).
> say the
< the cat sat

# Honesty preserved: a cyclic grammar with no learned boundary has no dominant
# STOP, so the step bound remains the backstop (D-prop1) — it streams, bounded,
# rather than inventing a halt it never learned.
> learn sequence: ping pong ping
< Learned 2 transition(s).
> say ping
< ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping pong ping
